(
  'The Secret Garden',
  'Frances Hodgson Burnett',
  'A lonely orphan discovers a hidden garden and transforms both the garden and herself.',
  'When Mary Lennox was sent to Misselthwaite Manor to live with her uncle, everybody said she was the most disagreeable-looking child ever seen. It was true, too. She had a little thin face and a little thin body, thin light hair and a sour expression. Her hair was yellow, and her face was yellow because she had been born in India and had always been ill in one way or another.

Mary had never cared for anyone, and no one had ever cared for her. When her parents died from cholera, she was sent to England to live with her uncle, Mr. Archibald Craven, at his estate on the Yorkshire moors.

The house was a strange place—large, gloomy, and filled with hundreds of rooms. Mr. Craven was hardly ever there, lost in his grief over his wife''s death. Mary was left to wander the grounds alone, with only the servants for company.

One day, a friendly robin led Mary to a hidden door in the garden wall. Behind it lay a secret garden that had been locked and forgotten for ten years—ever since Mrs. Craven''s death. The garden was overgrown and appeared dead, but Mary could see tiny shoots of green beginning to push through the earth.

With the help of Dickon, a local boy with a gift for befriending animals, Mary began to secretly restore the garden. As she worked in the fresh air and sunshine, her pale cheeks grew rosy, and her sour expression transformed into something approaching happiness.

Then Mary discovered another secret: her cousin Colin, Mr. Craven''s son, who she hadn''t known existed. Colin had been kept hidden in the manor, convinced he was going to die young like his mother. He was a difficult, spoiled boy who threw terrible tantrums.

Mary, having been disagreeable herself, wasn''t intimidated by Colin''s behavior. She told him firmly that there was nothing wrong with him except his imagination. Gradually, she convinced him to visit the secret garden.

The transformation was remarkable. In the garden, Colin discovered he could walk and even run. The children worked together, planting flowers and watching them grow. As the garden came back to life, so did the children. Colin''s health improved dramatically, and his father''s sadness began to lift.

When Mr. Craven finally returned to Misselthwaite Manor, he heard children''s laughter coming from the secret garden. There he found Colin—not the sickly, bedridden boy he had left behind, but a healthy, happy child running through the flowers. The garden had worked its magic on them all.',
