(
  'The Hobbit',
  'J.R.R. Tolkien',
  'A reluctant hobbit joins dwarves on a quest to reclaim their treasure from a dragon.',
  'In a hole in the ground there lived a hobbit. Not a nasty, dirty, wet hole, filled with the ends of worms and an oozy smell, nor yet a dry, bare, sandy hole with nothing in it to sit down on or to eat: it was a hobbit-hole, and that means comfort.

Bilbo Baggins was a respectable hobbit who enjoyed his comfortable life in the Shire. He loved his warm home, his pantry full of food, and his peaceful existence. Adventure? Excitement? Hobbits had no use for such things.

But one day, the wizard Gandalf arrived at Bilbo''s door with thirteen dwarves. Their leader, Thorin Oakenshield, explained that they were on a quest to reclaim their homeland and treasure from Smaug, a fearsome dragon. They needed a burglar, and Gandalf had recommended Bilbo.

Despite his protests, Bilbo found himself swept up in the adventure. The journey was perilous from the start. The company was captured by trolls, who wanted to eat them, but Gandalf saved them by keeping the trolls arguing until sunrise turned them to stone.

In the Misty Mountains, they were caught by goblins and brought deep underground. During his escape, Bilbo became separated from the others and stumbled into a dark cave. There, he found a strange ring lying on the ground and put it in his pocket.

In that cave, Bilbo also met Gollum, a slimy creature who lived on an island in an underground lake. They played a riddle game, with Bilbo''s life as the stakes. Bilbo won by accident, asking "What have I got in my pocket?" Gollum couldn''t answer and was furious.

When Bilbo put on the ring he had found, he discovered it made him invisible. This allowed him to escape Gollum and find his way out of the mountains. He reunited with the dwarves and Gandalf, though he didn''t tell them the full truth about how he escaped.

The journey continued through many dangers: giant spiders in Mirkwood Forest, imprisonment by Wood-elves, and a tense journey to the Lonely Mountain where Smaug the dragon awaited. Bilbo, using his ring and his growing courage, managed to sneak into the mountain and speak with the dragon.

In his pride, Smaug revealed a weak spot in his armor. When the dragon attacked the nearby town of Lake-town in revenge, a brave archer named Bard used this information to slay the beast with a single arrow.

But the dragon''s death led to a new crisis. Men, elves, and dwarves all claimed the treasure, and war seemed inevitable. It was only when an army of goblins and wolves attacked that the various armies united to fight their common enemy. In the Battle of Five Armies, many brave warriors fell, including Thorin.

Before he died, Thorin made peace with Bilbo, recognizing that the hobbit''s simple wisdom about the value of home and friendship was worth more than all the treasure in the mountain. Bilbo returned to the Shire, carrying only a small portion of his share, along with the ring and memories of his great adventure.

Back in his comfortable hobbit-hole, Bilbo was changed. He was no longer considered quite respectable by other hobbits, but he didn''t mind. He had stories to tell, songs to sing, and he had learned that there was more to life than comfort and respectability. Sometimes, even the smallest person can change the course of the future.',
