(
  'Animal Farm',
  'George Orwell',
  'Farm animals rebel against their human owner, only to find themselves under a new tyranny.',
  'Mr. Jones, of the Manor Farm, had locked the hen-houses for the night, but was too drunk to remember to shut the pop-holes. The animals of the farm were restless. Old Major, a prize-winning boar, had called a meeting in the big barn to share a strange dream.

"Comrades," Old Major began, "I have lived a long life, and I have come to understand the nature of our existence. We animals work and produce, yet we are given barely enough to keep us alive. All our labor is stolen by Man, who produces nothing yet lives in luxury. We must rebel!"

Three days later, Old Major died, but his words had planted a seed. The rebellion came sooner than anyone expected. Mr. Jones, drunk and neglectful, forgot to feed the animals. Driven by hunger, they broke into the store-shed. Jones and his men tried to whip them back, but this time the animals fought back. Within minutes, the humans were fleeing for their lives.

The animals could hardly believe their victory. Manor Farm was theirs! They renamed it Animal Farm and created Seven Commandments, the most important being "All animals are equal." Two pigs, Napoleon and Snowball, emerged as leaders.

At first, the farm thrived. The animals worked hard, motivated by the knowledge that they were working for themselves. Snowball planned to build a windmill that would bring electricity and make their lives easier. But Napoleon opposed the plan. When it came time to vote, Napoleon unleashed nine fierce dogs he had secretly trained, and Snowball fled for his life.

Napoleon declared himself leader and announced that the windmill would be built after all—claiming it had been his idea from the start. The animals worked harder than ever, with the loyal cart-horse Boxer driving himself to exhaustion with his motto: "I will work harder!"

But gradually, things changed. The pigs moved into the farmhouse and began sleeping in beds. When the animals protested, they found the Commandments had been altered: "No animal shall sleep in a bed with sheets." The pigs began trading with neighboring farms—the very humans they had rebelled against.

When the windmill was destroyed in a storm, Napoleon blamed Snowball and used this as an excuse to purge the farm of supposed traitors. Animals who confessed to crimes they hadn''t committed were slaughtered by the dogs. The Commandment "No animal shall kill any other animal" was found to read "without cause."

Boxer worked himself to collapse. When he fell, Napoleon promised to send him to a veterinarian, but the van that arrived was from a horse slaughterer. Squealer, Napoleon''s propagandist, convinced the animals that their eyes had deceived them.

Years passed. The farm was prosperous, but only the pigs and dogs lived well. The other animals worked harder than ever for less food than they had under Jones. One evening, the animals peeked through the farmhouse window and saw the pigs walking on two legs, wearing clothes, and playing cards with human farmers.

The Commandments had all been replaced with a single statement: "All animals are equal, but some animals are more equal than others." Looking from pig to man, and man to pig, the animals found it impossible to tell which was which. The revolution had come full circle.',
