(
  'The Adventures of Tom Sawyer',
  'Mark Twain',
  'A mischievous boy''s adventures along the Mississippi River, from whitewashing fences to witnessing a murder.',
  '"TOM!"

No answer.

"TOM!"

No answer.

"What''s gone with that boy, I wonder? You TOM!"

Aunt Polly was calling, but Tom Sawyer was already climbing out the window. He had been caught with jam on his face, and he wasn''t about to face punishment. Tom was a clever boy who lived with his Aunt Polly in the small town of St. Petersburg, Missouri, along the Mississippi River.

Tom was always in trouble, but he had a way of turning every punishment into an adventure. When Aunt Polly sentenced him to whitewash the fence on Saturday, Tom convinced the other boys that painting was a privilege, not a chore. By afternoon, the fence had three coats of whitewash, and Tom had accumulated an apple, a kite, a dead rat on a string, and other treasures—all traded by boys who paid for the honor of painting his fence.

Tom fell in love with Becky Thatcher, the new girl in town, though their romance was rocky. He attended Sunday school only to win a Bible by trading for tickets, and he made a spectacle of himself in church by releasing a pinch-bug that fought with a poodle during the sermon.

But Tom''s life took a dark turn one night when he and his friend Huckleberry Finn, the town outcast, went to the graveyard at midnight to cure warts with a dead cat. There, they witnessed a murder. Injun Joe killed Dr. Robinson and framed the innocent Muff Potter for the crime. Terrified, Tom and Huck swore in blood never to tell what they saw.

Feeling troubled and unappreciated, Tom ran away with Huck and their friend Joe Harper to become pirates on Jackson''s Island. For several days, they lived freely, swimming, fishing, and exploring. Back in town, everyone believed the boys had drowned. But on the day of their funeral, Tom couldn''t resist the dramatic moment—the three "dead" boys walked into the church just as the service was beginning.

Tom''s conscience tortured him about Muff Potter''s trial. Finally, despite his fear of Injun Joe, Tom testified in court, revealing the truth about the murder. Muff Potter was freed, but Injun Joe escaped through a window.

Later, Tom and Becky got lost in McDougal''s Cave during a picnic. For three terrifying days, they wandered the dark passages with only a small candle. Tom discovered that Injun Joe was also hiding in the cave. Finally, Tom found an exit, and he and Becky were rescued.

Becky''s father, Judge Thatcher, ordered the cave sealed to prevent further accidents. Two weeks later, Tom revealed that Injun Joe was still inside. When they opened the cave, they found the villain dead, starved and trying to dig through the door.

Tom and Huck returned to the cave and found the treasure that Injun Joe had hidden—twelve thousand dollars in gold coins. The money was invested for them, giving them an income that made them rich by the standards of the town.

Huck was adopted by the Widow Douglas, who tried to "civilize" him with regular baths, proper clothes, and school. Huck found civilization suffocating and ran away. Tom found him and convinced him to give it another try—at least for a while. After all, Huck couldn''t be in Tom''s new gang of robbers unless he was respectable.

As summer ended, Tom and Huck looked forward to new adventures, knowing that nothing could keep them from finding trouble and excitement in the sleepy town of St. Petersburg.',
