(
  'The Great Gatsby',
  'F. Scott Fitzgerald',
  'A mysterious millionaire throws lavish parties while pursuing an impossible dream of the past.',
  'In my younger and more vulnerable years my father gave me some advice. "Whenever you feel like criticizing anyone," he told me, "just remember that all the people in this world haven''t had the advantages that you''ve had."

I am Nick Carraway, and in the summer of 1922, I moved to West Egg, Long Island, to learn the bond business. My small house sat next to a mansion owned by a man named Jay Gatsby, about whom the most extraordinary rumors circulated.

Across the bay in East Egg lived my cousin Daisy Buchanan and her husband Tom. Tom was a brutal, arrogant man from an immensely wealthy family. Daisy was beautiful and charming, but there was a desperation in her voice, a hint that she was deeply unhappy.

At their house, I met Jordan Baker, a professional golfer and friend of Daisy''s. Jordan told me that Tom was having an affair with Myrtle Wilson, whose husband ran a garage in the valley of ashes—a desolate stretch of land between West Egg and New York City.

My neighbor Gatsby threw spectacular parties every weekend. Hundreds of people came to drink his champagne and dance to his jazz orchestra, but few knew anything about their host. Some said he was a German spy. Others claimed he had killed a man.

One day, Gatsby''s chauffeur brought me a surprisingly formal invitation to one of these parties. There, I finally met my mysterious neighbor. Gatsby was elegant and gracious, with an extraordinary smile. But something about him seemed false, rehearsed.

Jordan revealed Gatsby''s secret: five years earlier, when he was a poor soldier, he had fallen in love with Daisy. She had promised to wait for him, but she married Tom instead. Everything Gatsby had done since—earning his fortune, buying his mansion, throwing his parties—was designed to win Daisy back. The green light at the end of Daisy''s dock, which Gatsby stared at each night, represented his yearning for the past.

Gatsby asked me to invite Daisy to tea, giving him a chance to "accidentally" meet her. Their reunion was awkward at first, but soon the old feelings returned. They began an affair, with Gatsby convinced that Daisy would leave Tom.

One hot summer day, the group went to New York. In a hotel room, Tom confronted Gatsby. He exposed Gatsby''s criminal connections—his fortune came from bootlegging and other illegal activities. Daisy, torn between her past and her present, couldn''t bring herself to leave Tom.

On the drive back, Daisy was driving Gatsby''s car when it struck and killed Myrtle Wilson, who had run into the road. Gatsby took the blame to protect Daisy.

Myrtle''s husband, mad with grief and believing Gatsby was driving, shot Gatsby and then himself. Gatsby died still believing that Daisy would call, that they would run away together. But she never called. She and Tom left town, leaving no forwarding address.

Almost no one came to Gatsby''s funeral—not the hundreds who had enjoyed his parties, not the business associates who had used him, and certainly not Daisy. I arranged everything and then left New York, disgusted by the carelessness of the wealthy.

Gatsby believed in the green light, in the future that year by year receded before him. He had an extraordinary gift for hope, and he died still reaching for his dream. "So we beat on," I reflected, "boats against the current, borne back ceaselessly into the past."',
